[[File:Dragon impling jar detail.png|left|130px]]
The '''dragon impling jar''' is the result of successfully catching a [[dragon impling]], requiring level 83 [[Hunter]]. The dragon impling is second only to the [[Lucky impling]] as the rarest and most difficult to catch [[impling]] in [[Impetuous Impulses]].

As can be done with all [[impling]] jars, the dragon impling jar can be traded in singularly to [[Elnock Inquisitor]] for three empty [[impling jar]]s. This is not recommended, due to the fact that dragon impling jars are worth vastly more than three empty jars.

The market value of dragon impling jars is considerably more than all but a few of the possible loot items from it, notably [[dragon darts]] or [[dragon dart tips]]. Their price is high due to the chance of said expensive items, the rarity of the dragon impling itself, as well as players opening dragon impling jars for [[Clue scroll (elite)|elite clue scrolls]]. Clue hunters will buy implings in bulk for the ability to obtain clues faster than any other method in the game for a high cost. You can't take dragon impling jars onto [[Entrana]], as looting them may give you weapons.

==Loot==
At current [[Grand Exchange]] prices, opening a dragon impling jar gives {{Coins|{{ImpValue|dragon|jar=yes}} round 0}} worth of loot, on average. This means opening dragon impling jars marks an average {{#ifexpr:{{#vardefineecho:profit|{{ImpValue|dragon|jar=yes}}-{{GEP|Dragon impling jar}} round 0}}>=0|profit|loss}} {{Coins|{{#var:profit}}}} coins per jar, however this does not include loot from clue scrolls.

On average, one would {{#ifexpr:{{#vardefineecho:profit1|50*({{ImpValue|dragon|jar=yes}}-{{GEP|Dragon impling jar}}) round 0}}>=0|profit|lose}} {{Coins|{{#var:profit1}}}} coins to get an [[clue scroll (elite)|elite clue scroll]] from dragon impling jars at current [[Grand Exchange]] prices, excluding the rewards from the completed [[Treasure Trail]]s.

